content: The gameplay and story have been great!

Its the spiritual sequel of Adventure Bar. Gameplay is you collect ingredients and cook some food to improve your tavern. You level up by eating foods. Character interaction is plenty too. Can be pretty hard especially on late game boss fights of you fight them unprepared.

Well-made, fun cooking & adventure game! Cute story elements as well. FYI, there aren't very many resources out there if you need tips, since it's new. But there is a recipe list, which really helps you avoid wasting ingredients. When deciding what to make for your menu, I recommend filtering by price so you can see which recipes will make the most profit, then getting those ingredients. (Black pepper is expensive but worth it. Mixed Salt goes into many lucrative recipes.) Good luck!

The gameplay is pretty good; I spent almost thirty hours this week playing the game. It's also very easy to get attached to the main character and sympathize with her plight because of the character dynamics. One minor issue was that the game doesn't have a pop-up screen that tells you if you've used the monster repellent or attractor. When I played with the sound off, I ended up accidently using five monster attractors at once.

Some UI improvements can be made. It is difficult to find ingredients on the menu when there are tons of them. Same goes for the recipes. I hope I can assign auto-battle skills, not just random execution. A list of dish combos once discovered already would be nice. Some bugs like stealing Trout Sashimi from Undine does not add to the inventory. Also a lot of NPCs are useless, would be good if they can add quests to discover recipes. Some recipes are really difficult to figure out even with hints

Mindless repetitive grinding. The gameplay loop is Get ingredients -> Cook -> Sell. Selling is straight forward, based on dishes' price and popularity. I love it. My only issue is while the character cast has diversity/ are individuals in story, their roles combat-wise have a lot of overlaps between the cast, only made somewhat distinct by their passives. Still, an absolutely lovely game if you enjoy shop management/RPGs. The combat is pretty intuitive, just be aware that elemental resistances will kick your booty if you don't heed them.

A great sequel to Adventure Bar Story! Some of the mechanics are slightly different but overall it is much more streamlined in the cooking portions of the game. More recipes are more complex than those in Adventure Bar, and I've caught myself getting hungry just reading though the list. Unfortunately, the RPG portions aren't quite as balanced as its predecessor, but Tavern Story makes it up by having better dungeon designs. I highly recommend this game to foodies and budding chefs alike!

This game is a lot of fun if you like atelier games and the like. The principle is basically the same, just with cooking - you want to make different dishes to make your tavern prosper and you therefore need to hunt monsters for more ingredients. It can get a bit long at times and the party system is not very intuitive to me. But other than that, it is very nice and addictive! I have been playing it again non-stop since they fixed the loading screen bug and am totally addicted to it. It has become my favourite mobile game as of now!

OMG! IS THIS A COLLAB BETWEEN RIDEON AND KEMCO...?! GODS! THANK YOU FOR LETTING ME EXPERIENCE THIS! Anyway, if you liked Adventure Bar Story, then you're sure to like this one as well! Aside from the storyline, the characters, and some new tools and recipes, the basic plot, the villain's looks and name, basic gameplay, and controls are all the same as Adventure Bar Story. The only complaints I have are the small gamepad, lack of BL, and the lack of differences between this and Adventure Bar Story. I mean, I adore ABS, but like, if you're just gonna do this, just call it ABS2. Oh well, I actually just started playing recently, so I can't really give an in-depth analysis, but I sorta got the gist of it. Love the game.

It's pretty awesome because it's a game like harvest moon and it has much more features. And I'd say running a tavern is more interesting than tending to a farm. So with that said, I can understand why it was longer than usual for kemco to release another title. I can tell much work was put into this.
